"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by the All Party Parliamentary Group on Population, Development and Reproductive Health, and Marie Stopes International&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;What role can DFID play in strengthening the health system?&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTo support the Ministry of Health to develop a longer term vision for the health system \n–\n and\n to develop\n innovative \nmechanisms\n \nand partnerships \nto finance it. \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTo encourage\n the government to work in partnership with providers such as MSI to fill gaps, scale up services and harness potential of private providers. \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTo encourage the \ngovernment to train and build the capacity of rural health workers particularly midwives, and to empower them to provide services in isolated rural areas. \n&#xa0;\nWhat should DFID be doing more of?&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nContinue to prioritise investment in health - prioritising sexual and reproductive health services which offer the most cost effective way to improve health and development indicators. \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPrioritise delivery and access to primary health care services in rural areas and for excluded communities.\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nContinuing to work with other donors to ensure co-ordination and pooling of resources.\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nProvision of technical assistance - particularly on health financing, infrastructure investments (\neg\n for supplies and commodities) and training health workers at scale.\n&#xa0;\nJanuary 2013\n&#xa0;\n \nhttps://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/228499/ICAI-Burma-health-management-response-aug13.pdf\n&#xa0;\n"